choice.explanation:
Let the state vector be |ψ⟩ = (-1, 2, 1)^T

The operator for P is:
P = \begin{pmatrix} 0 & 1/\sqrt{2} & 0 \\ 1/\sqrt{2} & 0 & 1/\sqrt{2} \\ 0 & 1/\sqrt{2} & 0 \end{pmatrix}

The operator for Q is: 
Q = \begin{pmatrix} 1 & 0 & 0 \\ 0 & 0 & 0 \\ 0 & 0 & -1 \end{pmatrix}

To find the probability, we first apply P to get the state after measuring P:
|ψ'\rangle = P|ψ⟩ = \begin{pmatrix} 0 & 1/\sqrt{2} & 0 \\ 1/\sqrt{2} & 0 & 1/\sqrt{2} \\ 0 & 1/\sqrt{2} & 0 \end{pmatrix} \begin{pmatrix} -1 \\ 2 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 1/\sqrt{2} \\ 0 \\ 1/\sqrt{2} \end{pmatrix}

This is the state that will give 0 for measuring P.

Now we apply Q to this state:
Q|ψ'\rangle = \begin{pmatrix} 1 & 0 & 0 \\ 0 & 0 & 0 \\ 0 & 0 & -1 \end{pmatrix} \begin{pmatrix} 1/\sqrt{2} \\ 0 \\ 1/\sqrt{2} \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 1/\sqrt{2} \\ 0 \\ -1/\sqrt{2} \end{pmatrix}

The probability of getting -1 for Q is the squared magnitude of the last element: (1/\sqrt{2})^2 = 1/2

Therefore, the probability is 1/2.

ANSWER: C

